<br>
What we are dealing with is an urban legend. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/bfirionavie.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jaranna>Jaranna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 886<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/30/03 3:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm44.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=202.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wizards and Melee</span><hr size=1> It is my opinion that Concussion has 2 aggro components.  The aggro for casting the spell, and the aggro reduction that is the spell's effect.<br>
<br>
Casting Concussion on a mob causes aggro.  This can be proven by casting on something that hasn't attacked you.  However, if it is resisted, the spell doesn't go into effect...like a standard nuke.<br>
<br>
This initial aggro component to Concussion is very low.  The reason people think Concussion still works if it's resisted is because they have a pause in casting nukes, which allows others to gain more aggro, even for only a few seconds. <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://webpages.charter.net/thewok/jarasig.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--><br>
